WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:04.200
This is the fine-structure constant — how strongly light and matter interact.

2
00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:08.600
Physics measures it. TFPT computes it — the one answer a short equation allows,

3
00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:11.600
fixed by just two numbers, and nothing else.

4
00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:14.900
Bold claim. So I'll also show you exactly where it could break.

5
00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:19.800
Think of TFPT as a compiler — a machine, not a table of lucky numbers.

6
00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:25.000
Two inputs go in: a tempo, c₃ = 1/(8π) — the rate set by the edge of space,

7
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.500
and a width, g_car = 5 — how many slots the carrier has.

8
00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:34.500
From those, the pieces build themselves: three families of matter,

9
00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:39.500
a sixteen-part block that is exactly one full generation, and the hypercharges.

10
00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:45.500
Then the key player — E₈. It isn't a force of nature; it's the auditor.

11
00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:51.500
The one rulebook where every piece locks together exactly one way — like a perfect crystal.

12
00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:58.000
And it closes for only that one tempo and width — so E₈ doesn't accept the inputs, it forces them.

13
00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:02.500
So what does the machine actually print out?

14
00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:08.000
Almost the entire Standard Model — exact and machine-checked:

15
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.500
the three forces and their charges, three generations, exactly one Higgs,

16
00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:19.500
all nine particle masses on a single ladder, the quark and neutrino mixings, both CP phases,

17
00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:24.000
and a built-in reason there's no neutron dipole — strong-CP is exactly zero.

18
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
The headline: the fine-structure constant is the single positive root of one equation.

19
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Not chosen — forced. α⁻¹ = 137.0359992, under two sigma from experiment.

20
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Read the same edge as a horizon, and you also get cosmology — and gravity.

21
00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:46.500
But a list of numbers isn't physics yet. How does a static structure start to move?

22
00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:52.000
Through a clock. Two gears mesh: one of size five, the carrier; one of size six, the families.

23
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.500
Together they turn an order-thirty cycle — the same 2 · 3 · 5 that runs through everything.

24
00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:03.000
This clock has a gap: it always relaxes toward one single state, and never drifts back.

25
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
So the constants aren't tuned — they're selected. The machine settles on exactly one attractor.

26
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
That's the bridge: from frozen arithmetic to living dynamics.

27
00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:18.500
And that first input hides a gift.

28
00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:24.000
c₃ = 1/(8π) is the exact 8π sitting inside Einstein's equation for gravity.

29
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.500
Run the same atoms through the heat of a horizon, and the full law of gravity falls out —

30
00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:34.000
both constants fixed, even the cosmological constant, set by α.

31
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.800
The same 1/(8π) shows up three independent ways. Hard to call that an accident.

32
00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:45.000
Small whole numbers raise a fair worry: is this just numerology?

33
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.500
So we tried to break it ourselves.

34
00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:54.500
Of all the predictions, thirteen were frozen before we ever looked at the data.

35
00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:59.500
Then two hundred thousand random look-alike theories. TFPT hits all thirteen;

36
00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:03.500
the random ones top out at five.

37
00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:09.000
For α alone: of ninety-four thousand variants, exactly one lands in the measured window.

38
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And the seven arithmetic 'coincidences'? They're one object — the 2 · 3 · 5 of E₈ — seen seven ways.

39
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Odds a look-alike matches the whole scorecard: below 10⁻³⁰. Checked twice — in Wolfram and in Lean.

40
00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:28.500
The machine doesn't just explain — it predicts.

41
00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:34.000
Twenty-three falsifiable numbers. Today: nine already match, six are close, none miss,

42
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
and eight are still waiting for data.

43
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.500
sin²θ₁₂ ≈ 0.3067.  sin²θ₁₃ ≈ 0.0231.  A tiny gravitational-wave ratio.  Normal neutrino ordering.

44
00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:49.500
The near-term tests are real: neutrino mass from DESI and CMB-S4, proton decay at Hyper-Kamiokande,

45
00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:54.500
and the dark-energy equation of state at DESI.

46
00:03:54.500 --> 00:04:00.000
Each one is a tripwire. One clean miss, and the theory is wrong.

47
00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.500
So what is actually still open?

48
00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:13.500
Not a vague pile — three named, labelled handoffs.

49
00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:19.000
One published-theorem step from closing the central seam,

50
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
the clearly-marked bridges to external physics,

51
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
and one honest unit — because a theorem says pure numbers can never hand you a kilogram.

52
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Zero hidden mechanisms. Two inputs, one compiler — fully audited.

